The term '''Free Bahá'ís''' has been used by or about a small number of [[Bahá'í Faith|Bahá'ís]] that have attempted [[Bahá'í Faith|schism]] from the main body of believers of the Bahá'í Faith. More specifically, it is a form of belief that rejects the authority of [[Shoghi Effendi]], appointed in 1921 to lead the community following the death of [[`Abdu'l-Bahá]].
The term was first used by [[Hermann Zimmer]], who revived the earlier claims of [[Ruth White (Bahá'í author)|Ruth White]] that the ''[[Will and Testament of `Abdu'l-Bahá]]'' was forged. White's claim was widely rejected by other Bahá'ís of the time, including Bahá'ís who, like her, were enemies of Shoghi Effendi.<ref name=Covenant /><ref name="child-covenant">{{cite book |last=Taherzadeh |first= Adib | authorlink= Adib Taherzadeh |year=2000 |title=The Child of the Covenant |publisher=George Ronald |location=Oxford, UK |isbn=0-85398-439-5 |pages= 299–300 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | title = The A to Z of the Baha'i Faith | first = Hugh C. | last = Adamson | publisher = Rowman & Littlefield | year = 2009 | isbn = 0810868539 |p=121}}</ref><ref name="covenant-bahaullah">{{cite book |author= Taherzadeh, Adib |authorlink= Adib Taherzadeh |year= 1972 |title= The Covenant of Bahá'u'lláh |publisher= George Ronald |location=Oxford, UK |isbn= 0-85398-344-5 |page= 347 }}</ref> White was able to gather the support of a single Bahá'í in Germany, Wilhelm Herrigel, who took up her cause; only a few Bahá'ís followed him, and most repudiated him following his death in 1932.<ref name="balyuzi">{{cite book|title=Studies in Honor of the Late Hasan M. Balyuzi|chapter=Establishment of the Guardianship |last=Bramson-Lerche |first=Loni |editor=Moojan Momen| editorlink= Moojan Momen |date= 1988 |publisher=Kalimát Press |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author= Rabbani, Ruhiyyih |authorlink=Rúhíyyih Khanum |year= 1948 |title= Twenty-Five Years of the Guardianship |publisher=Bahá'í Publishing Trust |location=Wilmette, Illinois, USA |url= http://bahai-library.com/?file=khanum_25_years_guardianship#21 |page= 21 }}</ref>
Zimmer wrote a [[polemic]] attacking the [[Bahá'í administration]] in 1971, entitled ''A Fraudulent Testament devalues the Bahá'í Religion into Political Shogism'', which was widely distributed by [[Evangelical]] [[Protestant]] organizations in Germany, and later translated into English and distributed worldwide.<ref name=Covenant>{{cite web |url= https://bahai-library.com/momen_encyclopedia_covenant |title= Covenant, The, and Covenant-breaker |last= Momen |first= Moojan|authorlink= Moojan Momen |date= 1995 |website= Bahá'í Library Online |publisher= |access-date= December 22, 2016 |quote=}}</ref><ref name="balyuzi" /> Zimmer attempted to establish a group called "Free Bahá'ís" or the "World Union of Universal Religion and Universal Peace" along with Charles Seeburger of Philadelphia, but it is not clear that it actually came into being. An attempt to form a group in the 1970s was never documented to form.<ref name=Covenant/>
