[[File:Mahamayuri statue.jpg|thumb|Mahamayuri statue. [[Musée Guimet]]]] '''Mahamayuri''' ({{lang-sa|महामायूरी}} {{IAST|''Mahāmāyūrī''}} ("great peacock"), {{zh|孔雀明王}} ''Kǒngquè Míngwáng'', {{lang-vi|Khổng Tước Minh Vương}}, {{lang-ja|孔雀明王|''Kujaku Myōō''}}, {{lang-ko|공작명왕}} ''GongJakMyeongWang''), is a Buddhist tantric text dedicated to a goddess, and also the name of one of the five protective goddesses in the [[Buddhist Pantheon]].<ref name="HuntingtonBangdel2003">{{cite book|author1=John C. Huntington|author2=Dina Bangdel|title=The Circle of Bliss: Buddhist Meditational Art|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l3KmWbcq5foC |year=2003|publisher=Serindia Publications |isbn=978-1-932476-01-9|pages=24–25}}</ref><ref name="Dalal2010p218">{{cite book|author=Roshen Dalal|title=The Religions of India: A Concise Guide to Nine Major Faiths|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pNmfdAKFpkQC&pg=PA218 |year=2010|publisher=Penguin |isbn=978-0-14-341517-6|page=218}}</ref><ref name="Shaw2006p233">{{cite book|author=Miranda Eberle Shaw|title=Buddhist Goddesses of India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MvDKOK1h3zMC |year=2006|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=0-691-12758-1|pages=233, 339–341, 465 note 77}}</ref> Mahamayuri, also called Mahamayuir Vidya-rajni, is a peaceful goddess of wisdom (similar to [[Saraswati]] in Hinduism). In Buddhism, her demeanor is in contrast to the wrathful attitudes of male personifications of the [[Wisdom King]]s.<ref>Musée Guimet exhibit</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyohaku.go.jp/eng/dictio/kaiga/kujaku.html|title=About the Buddhist Painting, Peacock Myoo (Mahamayuri)|work=Kyoto National Museum|date=|accessdate=17 November 2017|language=en}}</ref>
Known as the 'Queen of the secret sciences' and Mahamayuri-vidyarajni, the ''Mother of Buddha'' in [[Mahayana Buddhism]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.carnivalglassworldwide.com/kamei-peacock-tail.html|title=Kamei Peacock Tail - Kamei Glass Co., Osaka|work=Carnival Glass Worldwide|date=|accessdate=17 November 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://paper.udn.com/udnpaper/POL0005/136113/web/|title=(孔雀明王咒) 的經典|work=paper.udn.com|date=|accessdate=17 November 2017|language=zh}}</ref> Mahamayuri had the power to protect devotees from poisoning, either physical or spiritual.<ref>{{cite book|author=Art Institute of Chicago|title=Notable Acquisitions at the Art Institute of Chicago|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=PfLzXKeVKzEC&pg=RA1-PA36|year=2004|publisher=University of Illinois Press|isbn=978-0-86559-209-4|page=36}}</ref><ref>Musée Guimet exhibit</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://tbsn.org/english2/news.php?id=469&classid=1|title= True Buddha Dharma-character Treasury - Mahamayuri|work=tbsn.org|date=|accessdate=17 November 2017|language=en}}</ref> The ''Mahamayuri'' text is a Buddhist dharani-genre text, containing magical incantations to treat snake bites, poisons and other maladies.<ref>{{cite book|author=SKR Rao|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Medicine|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QRvzRGn9QqkC&pg=PA73|year=1985|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-81-7154-255-0|page=73}}</ref>
Mahamayuri's [[dharani]] was translated into Chinese by [[Kumārajīva]] between 402 and 412 CE.<ref name="HuntingtonBangdel2003"/> It contains the only mention of the [[Rig Veda]] in the entire [[Chinese Buddhist canon]].{{cn|date=November 2018}}
