{{About|honorific title of the emperor of Japan|current reigning emperor of the [[Heisei]] era|Akihito}}
{{nihongo|Reigning Emperor|今上天皇|Kinjō Tennō|lead=yes}} or {{nihongo|[[Majesty]]|陛下|Heika}}, according to protocol, is the honorific title used in [[Japan]] to refer to the current [[Emperor of Japan]] instead of using their [[personal name]] (e.g. [[Hirohito]]), as is done in [[Western culture|the West]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Erskine|1933}}, quote: "In Japan, the personal name of the Emperor is never used by the people. He is always spoken of as the ''Heika'' or the ''Kinjo no Heika'' while living, and after his death is spoken of as the "Meiji Tenno" or " Taisho Tenno"</ref><ref name=izawa>{{Harvnb|Izawa|2011\P=180}}</ref> The only context where the personal name is used is when referring to their time before taking the throne (e.g. Prince Hirohito {{Nihongo2|裕仁親王}} ''Hirohito shinnō''). Members of the [[Imperial household]] have additional ''-miya'' type titles; the current Crown Prince is usually referred to by this title (e.g. [[Naruhito, Crown Prince of Japan|Prince Hiro]] ({{Nihongo2|浩宮}} ''Hiro-no-miya'').

==History==
Under the modern system, the {{nihongo|[[posthumous name]]|諡号|shigō|extra=colloquially ''gō''}} of the emperor will always match the {{Nihongo|era name or [[regnal year]] name|元号|gengō}}. However, this  {{Nihongo|"one generation one title"|{{nowrap|[[:ja:一世一元|一世一元]]}}|issei ichigen}} system was only implemented in the modern age of the [[Meiji Restoration]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Tanaka|2006}}</ref> In the past, the emperor's name never matched the era name, and the {{Nihongo|change of the era name|[[:ja:改元|改元]]|kaigen}} could occur any number of times. Additionally, some emperors had two ''gō'' titles, when reoccupying the throne in a process called {{Nihongo||[[:ja:重祚|重祚]]|chōso}}. One example of this was [[Empress Kōgyoku]], who later mounted the throne as [[Empress Saimei]].

